{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ENBVgzU5BNUkWtnVHeJ78J","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `users` and `users_roles` files are empty! This is why both users can't authenticate. The pods have empty file realm files. But the precondition showed that ops-user was able to authenticate (or at least the loop didn't show errors)...\n\nWait, let me reread the precondition log more carefully. Looking at step 40-51: the loop waits for ops-user to get a 200 response, then seeds the data. But actually there's no output from this block - it seems it might have timed out.\n\nActually looking again at the precondition log, the last verify step (line 54-55) shows no output after the verify command. \n\nThe code block at lines 40-51 also has no output, so ops-user authentication was probably failing during the precondition too. The precondition did create the secrets `es-file-realm-aggregate` and `user-provided-file-realm` using `--dry-run=client -o yaml | kubectl apply -f -`, but the real issue is that the statefulset doesn't mount these secrets at all. The ES pods are using the default `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/users` file which is empty, and there are 4 pods running (3 es-cluster nodes).\n\nLooking at the timestamps, the es-cluster pods are only 4 minutes old while the precondition ran about 25 minutes ago, which means the pods were restarted at some point. When they came back up, the file realm secret data might not have been available. The precondition creates the secrets for ops-user and report-user, but the wait/seed loop shows no output—it might have succeeded silently or failed without logging anything visible.\n\nThe statefulset doesn't actually mount either of those secrets, so the ES pods must be relying on the native file realm from their local filesystem. But if those local `users` and `users_roles` files are empty, I'm not sure how ops-user was authenticating in the first place. Let me check if the `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret is referenced anywhere else or if there's a separate mechanism I'm missing. The key issue is that the pods were recreated about 20 minutes after the precondition ran, so the timing doesn't line up for the secrets to have been properly loaded.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":309,"cache_read_input_tokens":47079,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":309},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"39858ae4-86af-4b3e-82cb-7dc53a4a82bc","uuid":"ed44dbde-1e21-4357-b624-408006eef4cd","request_id":"req_011CcgH45kJZXNBoZbtGfRbU"}
